    Bromine:

?    Storage tank enclosed and located in a diked area to reduce emissions to air in the event of a storage tank failure;
?    Storage tank not vented to atmosphere; sealed vessel;
?    Individual liquid containment system (dike) constructed;
?    Scrubber system installed to reduce vapor emissions to the air;
?    Ammonia vapor system present to control and eliminate bromine vapor;
?    Overfill protection systems in place;
?    Material for emergency response neutralization present;
?    Storage tank and transfer lines only under pressure during transfer;
?    Check valves installed to mitigate contamination of other systems;
?    ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operations associated with bromine;
?    Compatible materials of construction utilized;
?    Emergency response drills practiced concerning bromine releases;
?    Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;
?    Multiple Process Hazard Analyses completed for bromine systems.


    Carbon Disulfide: 

?    Use of a double-walled tank with a vacuum on the outer-shell to detect failure of tank;
?    Storage tank not vented to atmosphere; sealed vessel;
?    Individual liquid containment system (dike) constructed;
?    Overfill protection systems in place;
?    Maintenance of a water layer in dike area to act as a blanket on any released carbon disulfide (carbon disulfide is much heavier than water, tends to ?sink? beneath water);
?    Installation of a liquid carbon disulfide detector in diked area to trigger a DCS alarm; 
?    Limited use of flanged connections, reduced chance of leak in transfer lines;
?    Check valves installed to mitigate contamination of other systems;
?    ISO 9001 procedures in place governing operations associated with carbon disulfide;
?    Compatible materials of construction utilized;
?    Process included in Mechanical Integrity program;
?    Use of inert gas for flammable material transfer;
?    Multiple Process Hazard Analyses completed for carbon disulfide systems.

